## tl;dr

In Java 21 and later:

```java
    switch ( obj )
    {
        case Character c -&gt; System.out.println ( &quot;Is Character: &quot; + c );
        case Integer i -&gt; System.out.println ( &quot;Is Integer: &quot; + i );
        default -&gt; System.out.println ( &quot;Some other class: &quot; + obj.getClass ( ).getCanonicalName ( ) );
    }
```

In earlier Java, add `break` statements.


## `break` halts fall-through

I am guessing the error you mention (but neglected to document) was &quot;Illegal fall-through to a pattern&quot;. Your `switch` is trying to continue on through all the cases. But given the different class types of each case, that makes no sense. Hence that error (or so I am guessing).

The immediate fix is to add `break;` statements to stop the case-fall-through.

```java
static void test ( Object obj )
{
    switch ( obj )
    {
        case Character c:
            if ( c.charValue ( ) == 7 )
            {
                System.out.print ( &quot;Ding &quot; );
            }
            if ( c.charValue ( ) == 9 )
            {
                System.out.print ( &quot;Tab &quot; );
            }
            System.out.println ( &quot;character&quot; );
            break;  // &lt;----------
        case Integer i:  
            System.out.println ( &quot;An integer &quot; + i );
            break;  // &lt;----------
        default:
            System.out.println ( &quot;Neither character nor integer&quot; );
    }
}
```

Try it.

```java
App.test ( &#39;x&#39; );
App.test ( 42 );
App.test ( &quot;whatever&quot; );
```

Results:

```none
character
An integer 42
Neither character nor integer
```

## Simplify your code

Your IDE might suggest some improvements to your code.

One is replacing the unnecessary explicit unboxing of `.charValue`. Java will do that for you, auto-boxing.

```java
        if ( c == 7 )
        {
            System.out.print ( &quot;Ding &quot; );
        }
        if ( c == 9 )
        {
            System.out.print ( &quot;Tab &quot; );
        }
```

And really, this code does not help your demonstration. So let&#39;s stick to simple `println`.

```java
static void test ( Object obj )
{
    switch ( obj )
    {
        case Character c:
            System.out.println ( &quot;Is Character: &quot; + c );
            break;
        case Integer i:         
            System.out.println ( &quot;Is Integer: &quot; + i );
            break;
        default:
            System.out.println ( &quot;Some other class: &quot; + obj.getClass ( ).getCanonicalName ( ) );
    }
}
```

When run:

```none
Is Character: x
Is Integer: 42
Some other class: java.lang.String
```

## Java 21: Pattern Matching for `switch`

Java 21 brings more pattern matching. See [*JEP 441: Pattern Matching for switch*](https://openjdk.org/jeps/441). 

We can use the arrow operator `-&gt;` to execute code for that case. This syntax eliminates case-fall-through, so no `break` needed.


```java
static void test ( Object obj )
{
    switch ( obj )
    {
        case Character c -&gt; System.out.println ( &quot;Is Character: &quot; + c );
        case Integer i -&gt; System.out.println ( &quot;Is Integer: &quot; + i );
        default -&gt; System.out.println ( &quot;Some other class: &quot; + obj.getClass ( ).getCanonicalName ( ) );
    }
}
```

Simpler code, same results.

```none
Is Character: x
Is Integer: 42
Some other class: java.lang.String
```

For more info on pattern matching, see some good talks on YouTube etc., and read the Java JEPs. 

----------

By the way avoid using `char`/`Character`. That type has been essentially broken since Java 2, and legacy since Java 5. As a 16-bit value, `char` is physically incapable of representing most characters. Instead, make a habit of using Unicode [code point][1] integer numbers to work with individual characters. 


  [1]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Code_point

